            "id": "394f6c9bcc174c35b77ff",
            "questionText": "A proton with a charge of $!$1.602 \\times 10^{-19}~C$!$ and a mass of $!$1.672 \\times 10^{-27}~kg$!$ is injected perpendicularly into a uniform magnetic field of strength $!$0.5~T$!$. If the proton's initial velocity is $!$5 \\times 10^6~m/s$!$, calculate the radius of its circular path after it has lost half of its initial kinetic energy, assuming the magnetic field remains constant.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "966db1d0032b4a87a69a0",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula for the magnetic force acting on a charged particle moving in a magnetic field. Which of the following options correctly represents the expression for this force?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f69857d1-d285-419d-8458-a425ac5cf3d5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = q E$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = q vB$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = \\frac{mv^2}{r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = \\frac{qB}{v}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "b14868d7da80430a98673",
                    "stepText": "Now, consider the centripetal force required for circular motion. Which of the following formulas correctly expresses the centripetal force acting on a particle moving at speed $!$v$!$ in a circle of radius $!$r$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f34446c8-9452-48c0-ab50-0cb3fd1b9679"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = \\frac{mv^2}{r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = q vB$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = q E$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = \\frac{m}{r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "736d091ae5bb4c6590bb6",
                    "stepText": "Great! Next, by setting the magnetic force equal to the centripetal force, you can derive an expression for the radius of the circular path. Which of the following expressions correctly represents the radius in terms of mass, speed, charge, and magnetic field?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f34446c8-9452-48c0-ab50-0cb3fd1b9679",
                        "f69857d1-d285-419d-8458-a425ac5cf3d5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{mv}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{qB}{mv}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{qE}{mv}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{mv^2}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "d95ce228735541a796a5d",
                    "stepText": "Now, note that the proton loses half of its initial kinetic energy. Since kinetic energy is proportional to $!$v^2$!$, this reduction causes the speed to change. Calculate the new speed $!$v'$!$ if the initial speed is $!$v_0$!$ = $!$5 \\times 10^6~m/s$!$. (Hint: Express $!$v'$!$ in terms of $!$v_0$!$.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3.54e6"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2528a69f-0369-4021-ac12-870b5423cd8a"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "827bd2b733cf400782c69",
                    "stepText": "Finally, use the radius formula derived earlier along with the new speed to calculate the radius of the proton's circular path. Substitute the values: $!$m=1.672\\times10^{-27}~kg$!$, $!$v' = 3.54\\times10^6~m/s$!$, $!$q=1.602\\times10^{-19}~C$!$, and $!$B=0.5~T$!$. Compute the radius.",
