        {
            "id": "1bcc55ef1aec433fae2b1",
            "questionText": "An electron with a charge of $!$-1.602 \\times 10^{-19}~C$!$ and a mass of $!$9.11 \\times 10^{-31}~kg$!$ is shot horizontally at a velocity of $!$3 \\times 10^6~m/s$!$ into a uniform electric field between two parallel plates. The electric field strength is $!$2000~N/C$!$, and the electron travels a horizontal distance of $!$5~cm$!$ within the field. Calculate the change in the electron's kinetic energy during this time, assuming the electron enters the field midway between the plates and does not strike either plate.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "694f2ce194444a3cb3018",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the proper formula to calculate the force acting on a charged particle in an electric field. Which of the following formulas correctly relates the charge and the electric field to the force on the particle?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f69857d1-d285-419d-8458-a425ac5cf3d5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = qE$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = \\frac{q}{E}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = qmE$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "c127926db6564ca0b67a2",
                    "stepText": "Now, using the horizontal distance and the electron's velocity, calculate the time the electron spends within the electric field. What is the time in seconds?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.67e-8"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "s",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "493d8d92a40d4d4bba753",
                    "stepText": "Great. Next, we need to determine the acceleration of the electron while it is in the electric field. Which of the following formulas correctly relates the force we considered earlier to the electron's acceleration?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "5c33bb63-3c6d-413f-a1af-25385ab95845"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$a = \\frac{F}{m}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$a = \\frac{m}{F}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$a = qE t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "581a6236999a4b74b330f",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have determined the acceleration, let\u2019s compute the vertical displacement of the electron while it remains in the field. Use the relation that involves half the acceleration and the square of the time, i.e., the formula for displacement under constant acceleration. What is the vertical displacement in meters?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.0491"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "a5fee9d5-2b2a-4e9d-8caf-a83a70245740"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "b4b1a655101f4436954bb",
                    "stepText": "Finally, to find the change in the electron's kinetic energy, we need the work done on the electron by the electric field. Which formula correctly relates force and displacement to work done?",
                    "stepText2": "After that, using your computed values for the magnitude of the force and the vertical displacement, calculate the work (change in kinetic energy) in joules.",
